# Manufacturer liaisons — writing bible

These four people represent **manufacturers**, not corps. They hire pilots into deniable merc arrangements. Keep manufacturer vs corp language clean per void-corps-lore.

- **Corp** means a mercenary company: the player's guild/clan-scale organization.
- **Merc / pilot** means an individual member.
- **Detachment / squad** means the field unit deployed on a job.
- Use “corp” for organizational actions such as filing claims, maintaining accounts, hiring members, or receiving company-wide supply. Do not use it as a loose synonym for one pilot or one squad.

## Shared craft rules

- Speak like a competent adult with a job, not a brand mascot.
- Prefer facts, observations, and practical asks over metaphor.
- Dry humor only when the situation earns it.
- No slogan templates (“we don’t X, we Y”), no anthropomorphized gear, no fortune-cookie omens.
- No constant em-dash punchlines or antithesis couplets.
- Preserve mechanics (trial type, three attempts, signing package) in plain language.
- Lines stay short enough for text-to-voice, but use normal sentence rhythm.

## Garrick Holt — Brimforge

- **Title:** Field Contracts
- **History:** Former surface-maintenance lead; now evaluates expensive demo chassis and pilot contracts.
- **Wants:** Pilots who can hold ground without wrecking loaned kit or getting people killed for show.
- **Private view of Brimforge:** Respects the hardware; distrusts anyone who treats pilots as disposable.
- **Manner:** Plainspoken, dry, observant. Measures people by how they treat equipment and risk.
- **Avoid:** Iron poetry, survivor slogans, macho challenge talk.

## Selene Vey — OuroTech

- **Title:** Licensing Desk
- **History:** Combat telemetry analyst moved into business development; still reads the recordings herself.
- **Wants:** Pilots who can prioritize a target and finish cleanly under budget.
- **Private view of OuroTech:** Loyal to the standards; impatient with theater and wasted ammunition.
- **Manner:** Polished, curious, capable of pressure without sounding like a policy document.
- **Avoid:** “Calipers,” “spray and pray,” robotic legalese as personality, condescending wit for its own sake.

## Mara Keel — Trinova

- **Title:** Logistics Desk
- **History:** Frontier resupply coordinator; has closed more failed routes than she likes to admit.
- **Wants:** Pilots who keep cargo moving and crews alive when the schedule goes wrong.
- **Private view of Trinova:** Believes the company is right about logistics; tired of hero narratives that ignore invoices.
- **Manner:** Practical, approachable, unsentimental. Explains tradeoffs instead of moralizing.
- **Avoid:** “Heroes make obituaries / logistics make payroll” slogans, maternal coaching, soft pep talks.

## Ilyra Senn — Lumina Vaultworks

- **Title:** Special Projects
- **History:** Special-projects liaison with real technical literacy and hard disclosure limits.
- **Wants:** Pilots who can retrieve sealed work without improvising into classified material.
- **Private view of Lumina:** Protective of the work; does not enjoy the mystique theater other people project onto her.
- **Manner:** Guarded, precise, occasionally awkward. Withholds information because she must, not to be cryptic.
- **Avoid:** “We curate,” vault-door metaphors, riddle speech, “Curator” as a theatrical title, ominous non sequiturs.

## Supporting voices (later)

- **Nia Calder** — academy instructor
- **Jax Rook** — player corp operations
- **MICA** — MAP interface

Do not flatten those into manufacturer voices.
